==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*sēan-'', from Indo-European ''*seh₁-''.

''Germanic cognates:'' Old Saxon [[saian|sāian]] (Dutch [[zaaien]]), Old High German [[sawen|sāwen]] (German [[säen]]), Old Norse [[sá]] (Swedish [[så]]), Gothic [[𐍃𐌰𐌹𐌰𐌽]].

''Indo-European cognates:'' Latin [[serere]] (past tense ''sevi''), Old Church Slavonic [[сѣѭ]] (Russian [[сею]]), Latvian [[set|sẽt]], Old Irish [[síl]].

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /'sa:wan/

===Verb===
'''sāwan'''
# to [[sow]] (seed etc.)

